    "# Common Statistical Tests Are Linear Models\n",
    "\n",
    "**Based on:** Jonas Kristoffer Lindeløv, *Common Statistical Tests Are Linear Models (or: How to Teach Stats)*, 2019.  \n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "## Goal of This Notebook\n",
    "\n",
    "This notebook uses runnable Python examples to show how four familiar statistical tests are connected through the same regression idea:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. Student’s t-test  \n",
    "2. Mann–Whitney U test  \n",
    "3. Wilcoxon signed-rank test  \n",
    "4. Wald test  \n",
    "\n",
    "The main idea from Lindeløv’s article is that many common statistical tests can be written as linear models.\n",
    "\n",
    "A simple linear model can be written as:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "y_i = \\beta_0 + \\beta_1 x_i + \\varepsilon_i\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "where:\n",
    "\n",
    "- $$y_i$$ is the response variable,\n",
    "- $$x_i$$ is the predictor or group indicator,\n",
    "- $$\\beta_0$$ is the intercept,\n",
    "- $$\\beta_1$$ is the effect of the predictor which is given by the slope,\n",
    "- $$\\varepsilon_i$$ is the residual error.\n",
    "\n",
    "Most of these tests can then be understood as testing whether a model coefficient is zero:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "H_0: \\beta_1 = 0\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "That means the null hypothesis usually asks whether the predictor has no effect on the response.\n",
    "\n",
    "For example, in a two-sample comparison, $$x_i$$ may indicate group membership:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "x_i =\n",
    "\\begin{cases}\n",
    "0, & \\text{control group} \\\\\n",
    "1, & \\text{treatment group}\n",
    "\\end{cases}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Then the model becomes:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "y_i = \\beta_0 + \\beta_1 x_i + \\varepsilon_i\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "In this case:\n",
    "\n",
    "- $$\\beta_0$$ is the mean of the control group,\n",
    "- $$\\beta_1$$ is the difference between the treatment mean and the control mean.\n",
    "\n",
    "Therefore, testing:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "H_0: \\beta_1 = 0\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "is the same as testing whether the two groups differ.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "## Key Idea\n",
    "\n",
    "The four tests in this notebook differ mainly in how the data are prepared before fitting or interpreting the model.\n",
    "\n",
    "| Test | Regression interpretation |\n",
    "|---|---|\n",
    "| Student’s t-test | Linear regression on the original response values |\n",
    "| Mann–Whitney U test | Linear regression on ranked response values |\n",
    "| Wilcoxon signed-rank test | Linear regression on signed ranks or paired differences |\n",
    "| Wald test | General test of whether a fitted model coefficient differs from zero |\n",
    "\n",
    "For rank-based tests, the response variable is first transformed into ranks or signed ranks.  \n",
    "However, the core model-testing logic remains the same:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\text{fit a model} \\quad \\rightarrow \\quad \\text{test whether a coefficient is zero}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "So, although these tests may look different in traditional statistics textbooks, they can all be understood as variations of the same regression framework."
   ]
