    "# 1. Student’s Two-Sample t-Test as a Linear Model\n",
    "\n",
    "A two-sample Student’s t-test compares the means of two independent groups.\n",
    "\n",
    "The equivalent linear model is:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "y_i = \\beta_0 + \\beta_1 G_i + \\varepsilon_i\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "where:\n",
    "\n",
    "- $$G_i = 0$$ for group A,\n",
    "- $$G_i = 1$$ for group B,\n",
    "- $$\\beta_0$$ is the mean of group A,\n",
    "- $$\\beta_1$$ is the mean difference between the groups:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\beta_1 = \\bar{y}_B - \\bar{y}_A\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "So the two-sample t-test is equivalent to testing whether the group-difference coefficient is zero or in layman term if the slope is coinciding perfectly: \n",
    "$$\n",
    "H_0: \\beta_1 = 0\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "The test statistic is the **t-statistic**, which measures how large the estimated group difference is compared with its uncertainty:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "t =\n",
    "\\frac{\\widehat{\\beta}_1}{SE(\\widehat{\\beta}_1)}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Since:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\widehat{\\beta}_1 = \\bar{y}_B - \\bar{y}_A\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "the same statistic can be written as:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "t =\n",
    "\\frac{\\bar{y}_B - \\bar{y}_A}\n",
    "{SE(\\bar{y}_B - \\bar{y}_A)}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Here, $$SE$$ means **standard error**. It represents the uncertainty in the estimated difference between the two group means."
   ]
