    "# 2. Mann–Whitney U Test as a Regression on Ranks\n",
    "\n",
    "The Mann–Whitney U test is commonly described as a non-parametric alternative to the independent two-sample t-test.\n",
    "\n",
    "In the linear-model view, it is similar to the same group comparison used in the two-sample t-test, but instead of using the raw response values, we use the **ranks of the response values**.\n",
    "\n",
    "The model can be written as:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\operatorname{rank}(y_i) = \\beta_0 + \\beta_1 G_i + \\varepsilon_i\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "where:\n",
    "\n",
    "- $$G_i = 0$$ for group A,\n",
    "- $$G_i = 1$$ for group B,\n",
    "- $$\\operatorname{rank}(y_i)$$ is the rank of each observation after combining both groups,\n",
    "- $$\\beta_0$$ is the mean rank of group A,\n",
    "- $$\\beta_1$$ is the difference in mean ranks between group B and group A.\n",
    "\n",
    "So:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\beta_1 = \\overline{\\operatorname{rank}(y)}_B - \\overline{\\operatorname{rank}(y)}_A\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "The null hypothesis is:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "H_0: \\beta_1 = 0\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "This means that the two groups do not systematically differ in their ranks.\n",
    "\n",
    "In other words, the Mann–Whitney U test asks whether values from one group tend to be larger or smaller than values from the other group.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "The \\(U\\) statistic counts how many times an observation from one group is larger than an observation from the other group.\n",
    "\n",
    "For Group B compared with Group A, it can be written as:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "U_B = \\sum_{i \\in B}\\sum_{j \\in A} I(y_i > y_j)\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "where \\(I(y_i > y_j)\\) is an indicator function:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "I(y_i > y_j)=\n",
    "\\begin{cases}\n",
    "1, & \\text{if } y_i > y_j \\\\\n",
    "0, & \\text{if } y_i \\le y_j\n",
    "\\end{cases}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "If there are ties, the tied comparison contributes \\(0.5\\):\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "U_B = \\sum_{i \\in B}\\sum_{j \\in A}\n",
    "\\left[\n",
    "I(y_i > y_j) + \\frac{1}{2}I(y_i = y_j)\n",
    "\\right]\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "So \\(U_B\\) measures how often values from Group B are larger than values from Group A.\n",
    "\n",
    "It is also related to the rank sum of Group B:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "U_B = R_B - \\frac{n_B(n_B+1)}{2}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "where:\n",
    "\n",
    "- \\(R_B\\) is the sum of ranks in Group B,\n",
    "- \\(n_B\\) is the number of observations in Group B.\n",
    "\n",
    "Similarly, for Group A:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "U_A = R_A - \\frac{n_A(n_A+1)}{2}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "and:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "U_A + U_B = n_A n_B\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Therefore, the Mann–Whitney U test and the regression-on-ranks view are connected because both are based on the relative ordering of the combined observations.\n"
   ]
