    "# 3. Wilcoxon Signed-Rank Test \n",
    "\n",
    "The Wilcoxon signed-rank test is used for one-sample or paired data.\n",
    "\n",
    "This means that the signed ranks are centered around zero.\n",
    "\n",
    "So the Wilcoxon signed-rank test is equivalent in spirit to a one-sample t-test, but applied to signed ranks rather than raw paired differences.\n",
    "\n",
    "In this view:\n",
    "\n",
    "| Test | Model |\n",
    "|---|---|\n",
    "| Paired t-test | Intercept-only model on raw differences $$d_i$$ |\n",
    "| Wilcoxon signed-rank test | Intercept-only model on signed ranks $$s_i$$ |\n",
    "\n",
    "Therefore, the Wilcoxon signed-rank test can be understood as a regression-style test of whether the intercept of the signed-rank data is zero.\n",
    "\n",
    "The classical Wilcoxon signed-rank test is usually reported using a test statistic based on the positive and negative signed ranks.\n",
    "\n",
    "After calculating the paired differences,\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "d_i = y_{2i} - y_{1i}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "we remove any pairs where:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "d_i = 0\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Then we rank the absolute non-zero differences:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\operatorname{rank}(|d_i|)\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "The rank keeps information about the size of the difference, but ignores the sign temporarily.\n",
    "\n",
    "Next, the sign of the original difference is attached back to the rank:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "s_i = \\operatorname{sign}(d_i)\\operatorname{rank}(|d_i|)\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "The positive-rank sum is:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "W^+ = \\sum_{d_i > 0} \\operatorname{rank}(|d_i|)\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "The negative-rank sum is:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "W^- = \\sum_{d_i < 0} \\operatorname{rank}(|d_i|)\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "The Wilcoxon signed-rank test checks whether the positive and negative ranks are balanced.\n",
    "\n",
    "If the null hypothesis is true, then positive and negative signed ranks should roughly cancel out.\n",
    "\n",
    "The null hypothesis is:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "H_0: \\text{the median paired difference is zero}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "In the linear-model view, this becomes an intercept-only model on the signed ranks:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "s_i = \\beta_0 + \\varepsilon_i\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "where testing\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "H_0: \\beta_0 = 0\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "asks whether the signed ranks are centered around zero."
   ]
