    "# 4. Wald Test as the General Coefficient Test\n",
    "\n",
    "A Wald test is a general method for testing whether an estimated model parameter differs from a hypothesized value.\n",
    "\n",
    "For one regression coefficient, the null hypothesis is:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "H_0: \\beta_1 = 0\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Using the same two-group linear model,\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "y_i = \\beta_0 + \\beta_1 G_i + \\varepsilon_i\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "the Wald test asks whether the estimated slope coefficient is significantly different from zero.\n",
    "\n",
    "The Wald statistic is:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "W =\n",
    "\\left(\n",
    "\\frac{\\widehat{\\beta}_1 - 0}{SE(\\widehat{\\beta}_1)}\n",
    "\\right)^2\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Since subtracting zero does not change the numerator:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "W =\n",
    "\\left(\n",
    "\\frac{\\widehat{\\beta}_1}{SE(\\widehat{\\beta}_1)}\n",
    "\\right)^2\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "The expression inside the square is exactly the regression t-statistic:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "t =\n",
    "\\frac{\\widehat{\\beta}_1}{SE(\\widehat{\\beta}_1)}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Therefore:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "W = t^2\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "For one tested coefficient, the Wald statistic follows a chi-square distribution with one degree of freedom in large samples:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "W \\sim \\chi^2_1\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "So the Wald test is the general coefficient-testing framework behind the regression t-test.\n",
    "\n",
    "In ordinary least-squares regression:\n",
    "\n",
    "- the coefficient t-test tests $$H_0: \\beta_1 = 0$$ using a t-distribution,\n",
    "- the Wald test tests the same hypothesis using $$W=t^2$$ and a chi-square distribution.\n",
    "\n",
    "Therefore, for a single coefficient:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\text{Wald test} = \\text{squared regression t-test}\n",
    "$$"
   ]
