    "The numerical results show that the Student t-test and OLS regression coefficient test are exactly equivalent for two independent groups. The OLS slope is equal to the difference between the two group means, and the OLS t-statistic is identical to the Student t-statistic.\n",
    "\n",
    "The Wald test is also directly connected to the regression coefficient test. The Wald statistic is equal to the squared regression t-statistic:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "W = t^2\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Therefore, the Student t-test, OLS coefficient test, and Wald test are mathematically equivalent for testing one group-effect coefficient.\n",
    "\n",
    "For the Mann–Whitney test, the connection is not exact in terms of the test statistic, but the same modeling idea appears after converting the raw observations into ranks. The regression slope on ranks is equal to the difference in mean ranks between the two groups.\n",
    "\n",
    "For the Wilcoxon signed-rank test, the same idea appears after converting paired differences into signed ranks. The intercept of an intercept-only regression on signed ranks is equal to the mean signed rank.\n",
    "\n",
    "Thus, all four tests are the same in statistical spirit: they estimate an effect and test whether that effect is different from zero. The difference is the scale on which the effect is calculated: raw values, ranks, signed ranks, or a general model coefficient."
